Definition:
Spring Boot Architecture defines how Spring Boot applications are structured internally to provide auto-configuration, embedded servers, opinionated defaults, and production-ready features with minimal configuration.

Core idea:
üëâ Convention over Configuration

Spring Boot Internal Architecture
Main Components:
SpringApplication
Auto Configuration
Starter Dependencies
Embedded Web Server
Spring Container (ApplicationContext)
Actuator (optional)

High-Level Flow:
main() ‚Üí
SpringApplication.run() ‚Üí
Create ApplicationContext ‚Üí
Auto Configuration ‚Üí
Start Embedded Server ‚Üí
Application Ready
SpringApplication Class

Purpose:
Bootstraps and launches the Spring Boot application.

Responsibilities:
Create ApplicationContext
Load beans
Start embedded server
Trigger lifecycle callbacks

Code Example:
@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
    }
}

Output:
Tomcat started on port(s): 8080 (http)
Started DemoApplication in 3.214 seconds

Auto-Configuration Mechanism
Definition:
Auto-configuration automatically configures Spring beans based on:
Classpath dependencies
Existing beans
application.properties / application.yml

Key Annotation:
@EnableAutoConfiguration

How it Works Internally:
Reads META-INF/spring.factories
Loads AutoConfiguration classes
Uses @Conditional annotations

Common Conditions:
@ConditionalOnClass
@ConditionalOnMissingBean
@ConditionalOnProperty

Example: Auto-configured DataSource
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/test
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.datasource.password=root

What happens automatically:
DataSource bean created
TransactionManager created
JdbcTemplate configured
‚úÖ No XML, No manual beans

Disable Auto Configuration (Interview Favorite)
@SpringBootApplication(exclude = DataSourceAutoConfiguration.class)

Starter Dependencies
Definition:

Starters are predefined dependency descriptors that bundle commonly used libraries.
Examples:
| Starter                      | Purpose             |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------- |
| spring-boot-starter-web      | REST + MVC + Tomcat |
| spring-boot-starter-data-jpa | JPA + Hibernate     |
| spring-boot-starter-security | Spring Security     |
| spring-boot-starter-test     | Testing             |

Example:
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
</dependency>

What it Pulls Internally:
Spring MVC
Jackson
Validation
Embedded Tomcat

Interview Tip:
üëâ Starters do NOT contain code, they manage dependencies only.

Embedded Servers
Definition:
Spring Boot embeds web servers so applications run as standalone JARs.

Supported Servers:
Tomcat (default)
Jetty
Undertow

Default (Tomcat):
http://localhost:8080

Switch to Jetty:
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
  <exclusions>
    <exclusion>
      <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-tomcat</artifactId>
    </exclusion>
  </exclusions>
</dependency>

<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-jetty</artifactId>
</dependency>

Why Embedded Servers Matter (Tricky):
No WAR deployment needed
Faster startup
Microservices friendly

Spring Boot Application Lifecycle
Startup Phases:
main() starts
SpringApplication created
Environment prepared
ApplicationContext created
Bean instantiation
Embedded server starts
ApplicationReadyEvent fired

Lifecycle Events Example:
@Component
public class AppStartupListener 
        implements ApplicationListener<ApplicationReadyEvent> {

    @Override
    public void onApplicationEvent(ApplicationReadyEvent event) {
        System.out.println("Application Started Successfully");
    }
}

Output:
Application Started Successfully

@SpringBootApplication Annotation
Definition:
A meta-annotation that combines multiple critical annotations.

Internal Meta-Annotations:
@SpringBootApplication
=
@Configuration
@EnableAutoConfiguration
@ComponentScan

Explanation:
@Configuration ‚Üí Java-based config
@ComponentScan ‚Üí Scans beans
@EnableAutoConfiguration ‚Üí Auto setup

Equivalent Manual Configuration (Tricky):
@Configuration
@ComponentScan
@EnableAutoConfiguration
public class DemoApplication {}

Complete Example (End-to-End)
Controller:
@RestController
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping("/hello")
    public String hello() {
        return "Spring Boot Architecture Working!";
    }
}

Output (Browser/Postman):
Spring Boot Architecture Working!

INTERVIEW QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
Basic Interview Questions

Q1. What is Spring Boot Architecture?
A:
It is a layered architecture that provides auto-configuration, embedded servers, and starter dependencies to simplify Spring application development.

Q2. How does auto-configuration work internally?
A:
Spring Boot reads spring.factories, loads auto-config classes, and applies conditions based on classpath and configuration.

Q3. What is the role of SpringApplication?
A:
It bootstraps the application by creating ApplicationContext, loading beans, and starting the embedded server.

Advanced Interview Questions
Q4. Difference between Spring and Spring Boot Architecture?
Spring	                Spring Boot
------                  -----------
XML-heavy	              Auto-config
External server	        Embedded server
Manual dependencies	    Starter-based

Q5. How do you disable a specific auto-configuration?
A:
Using:
@SpringBootApplication(exclude = ...)

Q6. Can we create a Spring Boot app without @SpringBootApplication?
A:
Yes, by manually using @Configuration, @ComponentScan, and @EnableAutoConfiguration.

TRICKY INTERVIEW QUESTIONS (Very Important)
Q7. Does Spring Boot replace Spring Framework?
‚ùå No
‚úÖ Spring Boot uses Spring Framework internally.

Q8. Are starter dependencies mandatory?
‚ùå No
‚úÖ They simplify dependency management.

Q9. How does Spring Boot decide which beans to create automatically?
A:
Using conditional annotations like:
@ConditionalOnClass
@ConditionalOnMissingBean

Q10. Can we run Spring Boot without embedded server?
‚úÖ Yes
By excluding web starter or setting:
spring.main.web-application-type=none

One-Line Interview Summary (üî• Use This)
Spring Boot architecture simplifies Spring applications by combining auto-configuration, starter dependencies, and embedded servers to enable rapid, production-ready development with minimal configuration.
